Note:
Runa String Concatenation Function

Provides the concat() function for technical mode string concatenation.
This is the technical alternative to the natural "joined with" syntax.

Usage:
- Technical mode: concat("Hello", " ", "World")  
- Natural mode: "Hello" joined with " " joined with "World"

Both produce the same result but serve different coding styles.
:End Note

Note: Core concatenation function for technical mode
Process called "concat" that takes strings as List[String] returns String:
    Note: Concatenate multiple strings efficiently
    If length of strings is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    
    If length of strings is equal to 1:
        Return strings[0]
    
    Note: Calculate total length for efficient allocation
    Let total_length be 0
    For each string_part in strings:
        Set total_length to total_length plus length of string_part
    
    Note: Build result string
    Let result be ""
    For each string_part in strings:
        Set result to result joined with string_part
    
    Return result

Note: Overloaded versions for common use cases
Process called "concat" that takes str1 as String and str2 as String returns String:
    Return str1 joined with str2

Process called "concat" that takes str1 as String and str2 as String and str3 as String returns String:
    Return str1 joined with str2 joined with str3

Process called "concat" that takes str1 as String and str2 as String and str3 as String and str4 as String returns String:
    Return str1 joined with str2 joined with str3 joined with str4

Process called "concat" that takes str1 as String and str2 as String and str3 as String and str4 as String and str5 as String returns String:
    Return str1 joined with str2 joined with str3 joined with str4 joined with str5

Note: Convenience function for joining with separator
Process called "concat_with_separator" that takes strings as List[String] and separator as String returns String:
    Note: Join multiple strings with a separator
    If length of strings is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    
    If length of strings is equal to 1:
        Return strings[0]
    
    Let result be strings[0]
    For i from 1 to length of strings minus 1:
        Set result to result joined with separator joined with strings[i]
    
    Return result

Note: Alternative name that may be more intuitive
Process called "join" that takes strings as List[String] and separator as String returns String:
    Return concat_with_separator with strings as strings and separator as separator

Note: Performance-optimized version using buffer
Process called "concat_optimized" that takes strings as List[String] returns String:
    Note: High-performance concatenation for large numbers of strings
    If length of strings is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    
    If length of strings is equal to 1:
        Return strings[0]
    
    Note: Use StringBuilder pattern for efficiency
    Let builder be create_string_builder()
    For each string_part in strings:
        Call append_to_builder with builder as builder and text as string_part
    
    Return finalize_builder with builder as builder

Note: StringBuilder-like functionality  
Type called "StringBuilder":
    buffer as List[String]
    total_length as Integer

Process called "create_string_builder" returns StringBuilder:
    Return StringBuilder with:
        buffer as list containing
        total_length as 0

Process called "append_to_builder" that takes builder as StringBuilder and text as String returns None:
    Add text to builder.buffer
    Set builder.total_length to builder.total_length plus length of text

Process called "finalize_builder" that takes builder as StringBuilder returns String:
    Note: Convert StringBuilder to final string
    Return concat with strings as builder.buffer

Note: Template string functionality  
Process called "template" that takes template_string as String and values as Dictionary[String, String] returns String:
    Note: Simple template string replacement like "Hello {name}!"
    Let result be template_string
    
    For each key, value in values:
        Let placeholder be "{" joined with key joined with "}"
        Set result to replace_all_occurrences with text as result and search as placeholder and replacement as value
    
    Return result

Process called "replace_all_occurrences" that takes text as String and search as String and replacement as String returns String:
    Note: Replace all occurrences of search with replacement
    Let result be text
    Let search_pos be find_substring with text as result and search as search
    
    While search_pos is not equal to -1:
        Let before_part be substring with text as result and start as 0 and end as search_pos
        Let after_part be substring with text as result and start as search_pos plus length of search
        Set result to before_part joined with replacement joined with after_part
        
        Note: Continue searching from after the replacement
        Set search_pos to find_substring with text as result and search as search and start as search_pos plus length of replacement
    
    Return result

Note: String utility functions
Process called "find_substring" that takes text as String and search as String returns Integer:
    Note: Find first occurrence of search in text, return -1 if not found
    Let text_len be length of text
    Let search_len be length of search
    
    If search_len is greater than text_len:
        Return -1
    
    For i from 0 to text_len minus search_len:
        Let matches be true
        For j from 0 to search_len minus 1:
            If character_at with text as text and position as i plus j is not equal to character_at with text as search and position as j:
                Set matches to false
                Break
        If matches:
            Return i
    
    Return -1

Process called "find_substring" that takes text as String and search as String and start as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Find first occurrence of search in text starting from position
    Let text_len be length of text
    Let search_len be length of search
    
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    
    If search_len is greater than text_len or start is greater than text_len minus search_len:
        Return -1
    
    For i from start to text_len minus search_len:
        Let matches be true
        For j from 0 to search_len minus 1:
            If character_at with text as text and position as i plus j is not equal to character_at with text as search and position as j:
                Set matches to false
                Break
        If matches:
            Return i
    
    Return -1

Process called "substring" that takes text as String and start as Integer and end as Integer returns String:
    Note: Extract substring from start to end (exclusive)
    Let text_len be length of text
    
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    If end is greater than text_len:
        Set end to text_len
    If start is greater than or equal to end:
        Return ""
    
    Let result be ""
    For i from start to end minus 1:
        Set result to result joined with character_at with text as text and position as i
    
    Return result

Process called "character_at" that takes text as String and position as Integer returns String:
    Note: Get character at specific position
    If position is less than 0 or position is greater than or equal to length of text:
        Return ""
    
    Note: This would typically use built-in string indexing
    Let chars be text as List[String]
    Return chars[position]

Note: Export functions for use in other modules
Export concat
Export concat_with_separator  
Export join
Export template
Export StringBuilder
Export create_string_builder
Export append_to_builder
Export finalize_builder